President Biden has announced the establishment of the first-ever White House Office of Gun Violence Prevention. The office will be overseen by Vice President Harris and will focus on implementing and expanding upon the executive actions and legislation related to gun violence prevention. The office will work to coordinate efforts between states and ensure the proper implementation of gun safety legislation. The President believes that this office will save lives and address the gun violence epidemic in the country. Additionally, the President signed a bipartisan law to improve the organ transplant system, eliminating the funding cap and allowing for more resources to modernize the system. The President will also host Pacific Islands Forum leaders at the White House to discuss climate change, economic growth, and sustainable development. The article also mentions the ongoing negotiations between the UAW and auto manufacturers, the potential government shutdown, and the President's remarks at a fundraiser.